  "descriptions": [
    {
      "descrType": "Overview",
      "description": "The F-22 Raptor is a fifth-generation, single-seat, twin-engine, all-weather stealth tactical fighter aircraft. Developed by Lockheed Martin for the United States Air Force, it combines supercruise capability, supermaneuverability, stealth, and integrated avionics in a single airframe. The F-22 entered service with the USAF in December 2005 and remains the most capable air superiority fighter in operational service. A total of 195 aircraft were produced before production ended in 2011.",
      "shortDescription": "Fifth-generation stealth air superiority fighter operated by the United States Air Force.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Design",
      "description": "The F-22 airframe uses blended-wing-body construction with a diamond-delta wing planform and twin canted vertical stabilizers. The aircraft's shaping and radar-absorbent materials provide very low radar cross-section. Two Pratt &amp; Whitney F119 augmented turbofan engines give it supercruise capability at approximately Mach 1.82 without afterburner. Internal weapons bays carry six AIM-120 AMRAAMs and two AIM-9 Sidewinders in the air-superiority configuration, preserving the aircraft&#x27;s stealth signature. The AN/APG-77 AESA radar and AN/ALR-94 electronic warfare system provide advanced sensor fusion.",
      "shortDescription": "Blended-wing-body stealth airframe with internal weapons bays and F119 turbofan engines.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Usage",
      "description": "The F-22 has seen combat in Syria starting September 2014 and continues to serve as the primary USAF air superiority asset. It is operated exclusively by the United States Air Force; foreign sales have been prohibited by US law since 1997. The aircraft is expected to remain in service until the 2030s when it will begin to be replaced by the Next Generation Air Dominance (NGAD) platform.",
      "shortDescription": "Operated exclusively by the USAF; saw first combat in Syria in 2014.",
      "classification": "U"
    }
  ],
